# Final Demonstration

## Repository Notes
The final working code for the robot is contained in this section of the repository. Earlier labs and development versions were retained separately, but this folder contains the finalized demonstration code used for the completed project.

Additional documentation, images, and demonstration material are included in the "Final Version Folder" in the repository to show the development process and final results.

## Project Overview
This project is the final implementation of a Romi robot designed to complete a line-following course using sensor feedback, motor control, and finite-state-machine logic. The robot was developed with skills we learned throughout the quarter and refined into a final working system 
capable of navigating the course with minimal user interaction after launch.

The final code combines all major components of the project into one integrated system. These components include motor actuation, encoder feedback, line sensor processing, proportional control, and high-level navigation logic. 
Together, they allow the robot to detect the path, follow it, respond to course features, and complete the final demonstration route.

---

## What the Final Code Does
The final code controls the robot from startup through course completion. Once started, the robot reads data from its line sensors to detect its position relative to the path. Based on this sensor data, the control system adjusts the speed of the left and right motors 
so the robot stays centered on the line.

In addition to basic line following, the final code also handles larger course events using a finite state machine. Rather than treating the whole run as one continuous behavior, the program is divided into states that each correspond to a specific part of the course. 
For example, the robot begins by following the main line, then transitions through checkpoints, arc motion, turns, and recovery behaviors as needed. This structure makes the code easier to debug, tune, and expand.

The robot uses encoder feedback to estimate wheel movement and distance traveled. This helps the system determine when it has moved far enough to transition from one section of the course to another. 
Encoder measurements are especially useful in portions of the course where sensor feedback alone is not enough, such as controlled turns or arc traversal.

