## Main Functional Components

### Motor Control
The motor control portion of the code is responsible for driving the left and right wheels. Motor effort values are sent to each motor driver so the robot can move forward, slow one wheel for turning, or perform corrective actions when it drifts away from the line.

### Encoder Feedback
Each motor is paired with an encoder that measures wheel rotation. Encoder readings are used to estimate speed and displacement, allowing the robot to make more reliable movement decisions and improve repeatability on the course.

### Line Sensor Processing
An array of line sensors reads the surface beneath the robot and determines where the line is relative to the center of the chassis. These readings are converted into an error value, which represents how far the robot is from the desired position on the line.

### Closed-Loop Steering Control
The line-following behavior uses feedback control to reduce tracking error. When the robot drifts to one side of the line, the controller adjusts the motor speeds to steer it back toward center. This allows smoother and more stable motion than simple on/off corrections.

### Overall
The overall behavior of the robot is managed by a finite state machine. This logic determines what the robot should do at different stages of the course, such as:
- waiting for start
- following the straight path
- detecting checkpoints
- navigating curved or arc sections
- entering or crossing special course regions
- reacquiring the line if it is briefly lost

