## Design Approach
A major goal of the final code was reliability. Earlier versions of the robot could follow the line, but the final version improved consistency by separating the robot’s behavior into well-defined states and using sensor feedback more carefully. 
Instead of relying on one large block of logic, the final code uses a structured approach in which each behavior is activated only when needed.

This approach also made tuning easier. Motor control, line tracking, and course transitions could each be adjusted independently until the overall performance became more stable.

---

## Challenges and Improvements
One of the main challenges in the project was making the robot behave consistently across different parts of the course. Small issues such as sensor noise, overshooting a thick line, or transitioning too early between states could cause the robot to leave the path or stop 
unexpectedly.

To improve performance, the final code was revised to:
- better organize state transitions
- use encoder-based distance checks where appropriate
- improve line-following response
- include recovery behavior when the line was lost
- separate low-level motor control from high-level navigation logic

These changes made the final system more robust and easier to troubleshoot.

